00:01:57.320 --> 00:01:59.770
What's wrong with banking?

00:01:59.770 --> 00:02:02.727
So let me start
with a diagnosis.

00:02:02.727 --> 00:02:03.810
What's wrong with banking?

00:02:03.810 --> 00:02:05.670
Well there's a whole
long list here.

00:02:05.670 --> 00:02:07.510
What's wrong with banking?

00:02:07.510 --> 00:02:12.740
It's a very, very fragile
system, highly interconnected,

00:02:12.740 --> 00:02:16.150
lots of risks that's entirely
unnecessary in this system,

00:02:16.150 --> 00:02:18.610
and that's a distortion
to the whole economy.

00:02:18.610 --> 00:02:21.664
Meaning things just inefficient.

00:02:21.664 --> 00:02:22.830
Lots of governance problems.

00:02:22.830 --> 00:02:24.350
Governance problems
are basic problems

00:02:24.350 --> 00:02:26.766
where somebody makes a decision
and the other person who's

00:02:26.766 --> 00:02:28.540
impacted doesn't
have control over it.

00:02:28.540 --> 00:02:30.420
That's a basic
governance problem.

00:02:30.420 --> 00:02:32.570
And because this
is a system that

00:02:32.570 --> 00:02:34.830
doesn't work if
you leave it alone,

00:02:34.830 --> 00:02:36.300
it requires good regulation.

00:02:36.300 --> 00:02:37.880
And part of the
problem with it is

00:02:37.880 --> 00:02:40.300
it's not regulated
effectively to make

00:02:40.300 --> 00:02:43.300
it better, to help it to
from itself, basically,

00:02:43.300 --> 00:02:45.350
or from the people in it.

00:02:45.350 --> 00:02:47.970
And as a result of that, it
doesn't support the economy.

00:02:47.970 --> 00:02:50.200
It's part of the
infrastructure, you could say,

00:02:50.200 --> 00:02:53.990
of the economy that's just
not working very well.

00:02:53.990 --> 00:02:55.600
What makes it so fragile?

00:02:55.600 --> 00:02:57.690
Well the first thing--
and the one of them

00:02:57.690 --> 00:02:59.380
that I'm going to
talk about a lot--

00:02:59.380 --> 00:03:03.000
is that there's just a lot of
reliance on dept in the system.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:04.960
Just a lot of borrowing.

00:03:04.960 --> 00:03:07.490
The way banks and
many, many institutions

00:03:07.490 --> 00:03:11.320
fund what they do is
borrow money, make promises

00:03:11.320 --> 00:03:12.080
to pay later.

00:03:12.080 --> 00:03:13.560
And not just any money.

00:03:13.560 --> 00:03:15.224
They promise to
depositors that they

00:03:15.224 --> 00:03:16.390
can get their money anytime.

00:03:16.390 --> 00:03:19.500
They promise overnight
creditors that they

00:03:19.500 --> 00:03:21.130
can get their money tomorrow.

00:03:21.130 --> 00:03:22.720
They promise lots of people.

00:03:22.720 --> 00:03:25.570
And there is not enough
ability in the system

00:03:25.570 --> 00:03:27.950
to absorb the losses
should they happen.

00:03:27.950 --> 00:03:29.590
So and then it's
all interconnected.

00:03:29.590 --> 00:03:32.460
In other words, I owe you,
and you owe somebody else,

00:03:32.460 --> 00:03:34.150
but then somebody
else might owe me,

00:03:34.150 --> 00:03:36.880
and so it's all
very interconnected.

00:03:36.880 --> 00:03:39.529
And the regulation has
enormous flaws in it.

00:03:39.529 --> 00:03:41.070
The way it's
structured, the way it's

00:03:41.070 --> 00:03:45.180
measured, the way they can get
around it, all of those things

00:03:45.180 --> 00:03:49.920
make this regulation basically
incredibly ineffective.

00:03:49.920 --> 00:03:52.570
So here is sort of
a system for you.

00:03:52.570 --> 00:03:56.090
This system has this-- they'll
call it shadow banking.

00:03:56.090 --> 00:03:57.790
There are lots of
institutions outside,

00:03:57.790 --> 00:03:59.830
other institutions
inter-connected with it

00:03:59.830 --> 00:04:01.680
in numerous ways.

00:04:01.680 --> 00:04:03.172
If you kind of
step back from it,

00:04:03.172 --> 00:04:05.630
and there's somebody putting
money in the bank and somebody

00:04:05.630 --> 00:04:09.190
borrowing money somewhere,
and we have inter-mediation

00:04:09.190 --> 00:04:13.409
in between them, somehow
there's numerous layers there.

00:04:13.409 --> 00:04:15.200
And I think that in
the talk about Iceland,

00:04:15.200 --> 00:04:17.350
you saw how
interconnected systems can

00:04:17.350 --> 00:04:19.730
get with self-dealing
and self-ownership

00:04:19.730 --> 00:04:22.550
and lending to
yourself and all that.

00:04:22.550 --> 00:04:25.080
The question for society,
of course, is going to be

00:04:25.080 --> 00:04:27.810
is there value generated in
every one of these places

00:04:27.810 --> 00:04:30.550
that somehow has a reason
for existing in this world?

00:04:30.550 --> 00:04:34.260
Somebody wanted to create this
institution outside the balance

00:04:34.260 --> 00:04:37.310
sheet of this bank, or
outside somewhere else,

00:04:37.310 --> 00:04:41.770
and interacting in another layer
with the rest of the system.

00:04:41.770 --> 00:04:44.530
Are we sure that's
a good thing to have

00:04:44.530 --> 00:04:47.850
such a complicated system?

00:04:47.850 --> 00:04:51.990
So then when the system gets to
be like this-- very fragile--

00:04:51.990 --> 00:04:55.520
you get these contagion
effects, these dominoes,

00:04:55.520 --> 00:04:56.660
and all of that.

00:04:56.660 --> 00:05:02.934
And so you touch something and
the whole system can crumble.

00:05:02.934 --> 00:05:04.100
What does it mean, touch it?

00:05:04.100 --> 00:05:06.850
In 2008, what
touched it-- or 2007,

00:05:06.850 --> 00:05:09.990
it started-- what
touched it was a decline.

00:05:09.990 --> 00:05:13.560
A bubble burst in
housing in the US.

00:05:13.560 --> 00:05:16.220
In the grand scheme of
things, not a big thing.

00:05:16.220 --> 00:05:18.370
There were a lot
of bad loans made.

00:05:18.370 --> 00:05:20.290
Some borrowers defaulted.

00:05:20.290 --> 00:05:22.700
It was not an
amount of money that

00:05:22.700 --> 00:05:24.490
should take down
the global economy.

00:05:24.490 --> 00:05:27.710
And yet the system
was so fragile it

00:05:27.710 --> 00:05:29.310
couldn't withstand that.

00:05:29.310 --> 00:05:32.110
A bankruptcy of one institution
like Lehman Brothers

00:05:32.110 --> 00:05:36.780
just sent this whole
thing to implosion.

00:05:36.780 --> 00:05:39.360
Well, what are we
going to do about it?

00:05:39.360 --> 00:05:42.230
There are proposals
all over the place.

00:05:42.230 --> 00:05:45.130
One of them is
about the failure.

00:05:45.130 --> 00:05:47.010
So the bankruptcy
doesn't work, let's

00:05:47.010 --> 00:05:49.150
find a better way to fail them.

00:05:49.150 --> 00:05:50.835
So if they can't
pay their debts,

00:05:50.835 --> 00:05:53.150
they'll fail like other people.

00:05:53.150 --> 00:05:55.820
The problem with
that is they're very

00:05:55.820 --> 00:05:58.060
global-- I'll show
you an interconnected

00:05:58.060 --> 00:06:04.920
map across the world-- and they
live globally but die locally.

00:06:04.920 --> 00:06:08.740
So to die, if you have 2,000
subsidiaries, each one of these

00:06:08.740 --> 00:06:10.740
has to go into a
bankruptcy procedure,

00:06:10.740 --> 00:06:14.409
depending on the law in that
country and that's a mess.

00:06:14.409 --> 00:06:15.950
And that's what
happened with Lehman.

00:06:15.950 --> 00:06:18.410
This bankruptcy-- 80
different bankruptcy

00:06:18.410 --> 00:06:20.650
processes or more
started over the world.

00:06:20.650 --> 00:06:23.950
And it took years, it's
still barely done since then.

00:06:23.950 --> 00:06:26.570
And meanwhile, it freezes
everything and all of that.

00:06:26.570 --> 00:06:29.040
Banks can't kind
of go through that.

00:06:29.040 --> 00:06:31.960
So no matter how I'm
involved in the effort,

00:06:31.960 --> 00:06:35.940
it's part of the reform to have
the FDIC, the Federal Deposit

00:06:35.940 --> 00:06:40.280
Insurance Corporation, take down
JP Morgan-- good luck to all

00:06:40.280 --> 00:06:41.850
of us if that happens.

00:06:41.850 --> 00:06:45.890
These banks are much bigger than
Lehman was, and good luck to us

00:06:45.890 --> 00:06:48.340
if we should go into that.

00:06:48.340 --> 00:06:52.580
So that's not a great solution.

00:06:52.580 --> 00:06:56.780
The other is, let's make
sure that we kind of

00:06:56.780 --> 00:07:01.074
make them smaller and somehow
restrict what they can do.

00:07:01.074 --> 00:07:02.865
The problem with that--
so we have various,

00:07:02.865 --> 00:07:07.780
you might hear these words,
Volcker Rule, you can't do this

00:07:07.780 --> 00:07:09.280
and you can do that
and all of that.

00:07:09.280 --> 00:07:13.330
And these are potentially--
you talk about Glass-Steagall,

00:07:13.330 --> 00:07:14.840
I can't go into all of that.

00:07:14.840 --> 00:07:16.810
I'd be happy to talk
a little bit about it.

00:07:16.810 --> 00:07:19.250
We used to have a separation
between investment banks

00:07:19.250 --> 00:07:21.970
and commercial banks,
deposit-taking institutions.

00:07:21.970 --> 00:07:26.010
If you take deposits, you can
only do this and not that.

00:07:26.010 --> 00:07:27.490
That's a tough subject.

00:07:27.490 --> 00:07:32.610
The problem is it might help,
but if they remain fragile,

00:07:32.610 --> 00:07:36.260
and there's more layers and more
different little institutions,

00:07:36.260 --> 00:07:39.180
they can still be
failing at the same time

00:07:39.180 --> 00:07:41.360
or causing each other
to fail together.

00:07:41.360 --> 00:07:44.670
So you might not get rid of
that fragility of this system

00:07:44.670 --> 00:07:49.400
by some kind of structural
reform of who can do what.

00:07:49.400 --> 00:07:52.190
So you're not going to
the heart of the problem,

00:07:52.190 --> 00:07:54.570
to the heart of that fragility.

00:07:54.570 --> 00:07:56.950
And you could say, I'm not
going to bail them out,

00:07:56.950 --> 00:07:57.980
I hate bailouts.

00:07:57.980 --> 00:08:04.850
There were a lot of bailouts,
meaning creditors got paid when

00:08:04.850 --> 00:08:13.340
the bank couldn't-- AIG, Citi,
Bear Stearns, many other banks.

00:08:13.340 --> 00:08:15.430
Or the government
just invested in them

00:08:15.430 --> 00:08:17.970
so they could pay their debts.

00:08:17.970 --> 00:08:21.770
Troubled Asset Relief
Program, other things.

00:08:21.770 --> 00:08:24.460
The problem with trying
to say, I wrote in the law

00:08:24.460 --> 00:08:27.140
that I won't bail you out
is that, if the time comes

00:08:27.140 --> 00:08:30.080
and it's better to
bail them out than not,

00:08:30.080 --> 00:08:31.810
then you'll have
an emergency law.

00:08:31.810 --> 00:08:34.380
And it's hard for governments
to commit to that.

00:08:34.380 --> 00:08:35.990
They probably even
shouldn't commit.

00:08:35.990 --> 00:08:37.490
They should do what's best.

00:08:37.490 --> 00:08:39.330
But it's kind of a
hostage situation.

00:08:39.330 --> 00:08:41.820
In other words, you
can't quite commit

00:08:41.820 --> 00:08:43.360
to what you'd like to commit.

00:08:43.360 --> 00:08:46.100
Here is a network for you.

00:08:46.100 --> 00:08:48.630
Just the width of the
line-- this is just,

00:08:48.630 --> 00:08:50.080
I picked up
yesterday, so I don't

00:08:50.080 --> 00:08:52.890
show you the same
diagram as Iceland--

00:08:52.890 --> 00:08:54.520
but this is across
the globe for sure.

00:08:54.520 --> 00:08:58.949
20 countries and how the
flows of moneys between them.

00:08:58.949 --> 00:09:00.490
And these are
financial institutions.

00:09:00.490 --> 00:09:03.570
The thickness of the line
is just how much there is.

00:09:03.570 --> 00:09:08.620
In other words, the system
is knotted up together

00:09:08.620 --> 00:09:14.660
in a big,
impossible-to-disentangle knot.

00:09:14.660 --> 00:09:18.060
So are we stuck
with this system?

00:09:18.060 --> 00:09:19.420
Is it the best we can do?

00:09:19.420 --> 00:09:21.130
If we want to have
a financial system--

00:09:21.130 --> 00:09:25.710
a global financial system--
where we have a global trade

00:09:25.710 --> 00:09:30.130
and banks all
over, are we stuck?

00:09:30.130 --> 00:09:30.770
We're not.

00:09:30.770 --> 00:09:33.420
I want you to keep in
mind two analogies just

00:09:33.420 --> 00:09:35.510
for understanding
what I'm about to say.

00:09:35.510 --> 00:09:43.580
One is that banks' behavior
displays a form of addiction

00:09:43.580 --> 00:09:46.230
to certain harmful things.

00:09:46.230 --> 00:09:48.199
Harm to others in this case.

00:09:48.199 --> 00:09:49.740
So even to the banks
themselves, when

00:09:49.740 --> 00:09:52.070
you look at their entire
set of investors, including

00:09:52.070 --> 00:09:53.930
depositors.

00:09:53.930 --> 00:09:56.910
But they can't commitment
not to doing it,

00:09:56.910 --> 00:09:58.640
because it's too tempting to do.

00:10:02.130 --> 00:10:06.980
We have, inadvertently,
policies that

00:10:06.980 --> 00:10:11.160
encourage them to do
those polluting things.

00:10:11.160 --> 00:10:12.710
And then they do.

00:10:12.710 --> 00:10:15.590
We have to push
back so they don't.

00:10:15.590 --> 00:10:21.030
Analogy number two
is a speeding truck.

00:10:21.030 --> 00:10:23.640
You could think of what I'm
about to describe to you,

00:10:23.640 --> 00:10:26.510
for example, the
excessive amount

00:10:26.510 --> 00:10:29.830
of borrowing by banks
as a way of speeding.

00:10:29.830 --> 00:10:32.750
It kind of gets you there
fast if you're lucky.

00:10:32.750 --> 00:10:36.810
But you're also taking a
lot of risk of blowing up.

00:10:36.810 --> 00:10:40.270
In this particular case, if
you embellish this narrative--

00:10:40.270 --> 00:10:45.250
or this analogy-- the trucks
have subsidized insurance

00:10:45.250 --> 00:10:49.220
and their drivers get
out before the implosion.

00:10:49.220 --> 00:10:50.570
They're OK.

00:10:50.570 --> 00:10:53.232
But the collateral
damage is made.

00:10:53.232 --> 00:10:55.190
But they will say, let
me get back in the truck

00:10:55.190 --> 00:10:56.240
and drive again.

00:10:56.240 --> 00:10:57.920
That's my natural speed.

00:10:57.920 --> 00:11:01.290
That's the kind of
bankers' new clothes.

00:11:01.290 --> 00:11:04.310
The question will ask about
an ounce of prevention.

00:11:04.310 --> 00:11:06.030
Can we put a speed limit?

00:11:06.030 --> 00:11:09.510
Can we just stop that speed?

00:11:09.510 --> 00:11:11.340
So what am I talking about?

00:11:11.340 --> 00:11:16.120
I'm talking about putting
more equity in place instead

00:11:16.120 --> 00:11:19.380
of their finding themselves
with a lot of debt.

00:11:19.380 --> 00:11:21.890
So the bit concept-- it's
an accounting concept

00:11:21.890 --> 00:11:23.910
so it's very scary
sometimes, but it's

00:11:23.910 --> 00:11:26.780
a very simple concept-- is a
concept of a balance sheet.

00:11:26.780 --> 00:11:28.440
A balance sheet has two sides.

00:11:28.440 --> 00:11:30.950
One side is what
the investments are

00:11:30.950 --> 00:11:34.800
and the other side is how
it's funded, basically.

00:11:34.800 --> 00:11:37.230
There's borrowed money,
debt, liabilities,

00:11:37.230 --> 00:11:40.330
and there is the rest,
which is the down payment

00:11:40.330 --> 00:11:44.750
on a house, shareholder
equity, owner's money, equity.

00:11:44.750 --> 00:11:49.070
Well magically, if you fund your
investments with more equity,

00:11:49.070 --> 00:11:51.560
you are more resilient
to downslide.

00:11:51.560 --> 00:11:52.730
Homeowner's saw that.

00:11:52.730 --> 00:11:54.870
Companies see this all the time.

00:11:54.870 --> 00:11:59.870
So should there be the
Pac-Man that comes and eats

00:11:59.870 --> 00:12:04.930
some of your profits,
look at the bank

00:12:04.930 --> 00:12:08.114
that people are
wondering if it's still

00:12:08.114 --> 00:12:09.530
going to be able
to pay it's debt.

00:12:09.530 --> 00:12:12.060
Is it solvent or not?

00:12:12.060 --> 00:12:14.030
And look at the bank
with more equity.

00:12:14.030 --> 00:12:17.170
Still around because the
debt's still in place

00:12:17.170 --> 00:12:20.600
and it's the equity
that absorbs the losses.

00:12:20.600 --> 00:12:22.340
And also that makes
the gain, that's

00:12:22.340 --> 00:12:25.070
the fun part of it
when it works out.

00:12:25.070 --> 00:12:27.610
Because then they pay the
debt and take all the upside.

00:12:27.610 --> 00:12:28.860
That's the leverage.

00:12:28.860 --> 00:12:33.430
That's the effect of borrowing
that magnifies the upside.

00:12:33.430 --> 00:12:36.390
And the downside, should
there be another loss,

00:12:36.390 --> 00:12:39.590
uh-oh, the bank could
become insolvent,

00:12:39.590 --> 00:12:43.000
under water, like
homeowners whose

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:46.624
house is worth
less than they owe.

00:12:46.624 --> 00:12:49.040
And now, all kinds of terrible
things are going to happen.

00:12:49.040 --> 00:12:51.140
The government
can bail them out.

00:12:51.140 --> 00:12:52.920
But in the case of
banks, there will

00:12:52.920 --> 00:12:54.720
be all kinds of
disruptions to the system,

00:12:54.720 --> 00:12:56.810
because people may have
run away from them when

00:12:56.810 --> 00:12:58.070
they were afraid.

00:12:58.070 --> 00:13:00.190
All kinds of other things,
they stopped lending

00:13:00.190 --> 00:13:02.010
because they had to
sell their assets.

00:13:02.010 --> 00:13:06.690
All kinds of the mechanisms
that we saw-- those of you

00:13:06.690 --> 00:13:10.350
were paying attention in 2008,
or if you weren't, your parents

00:13:10.350 --> 00:13:10.850
were.

00:13:14.180 --> 00:13:18.310
So anyway, the question
is, why wouldn't we

00:13:18.310 --> 00:13:20.850
have a more resilient
banking system?

00:13:20.850 --> 00:13:25.710
Let's look at our biggest
bank, JP Morgan Chase.

00:13:25.710 --> 00:13:28.580
If you look at the balance
sheet of JP Morgan Chase,

00:13:28.580 --> 00:13:31.670
it has on one side
all kinds of assets.

00:13:31.670 --> 00:13:33.690
They want you to think
that there are lending.

00:13:33.690 --> 00:13:34.670
And that's their job.

00:13:34.670 --> 00:13:36.250
They're lending to
the real economy.

00:13:36.250 --> 00:13:38.880
God forbid, don't
touch their loans.

00:13:38.880 --> 00:13:41.410
But in fact, lending is
only a very small part

00:13:41.410 --> 00:13:42.540
of what they do.

00:13:42.540 --> 00:13:48.450
Say JP Morgan Chase defines, in
their assets, the IOUs of all

00:13:48.450 --> 00:13:52.330
their borrowers, their loans,
as part of their assets,

00:13:52.330 --> 00:13:53.220
$700 billion.

00:13:53.220 --> 00:13:59.090
The bank then has all kinds of
assets, derivatives in London,

00:13:59.090 --> 00:14:02.890
all kinds of other things,
physical commodities,

00:14:02.890 --> 00:14:04.890
you name it these days.

00:14:04.890 --> 00:14:07.320
You will be amazed
what they have.

00:14:07.320 --> 00:14:08.760
Lots and lots of things.

00:14:08.760 --> 00:14:11.660
And a little bit of cash.

00:14:11.660 --> 00:14:12.470
That the assets.

00:14:12.470 --> 00:14:14.560
And how are they funding this?

00:14:14.560 --> 00:14:18.670
$1.2 trillion of deposits.

00:14:18.670 --> 00:14:19.805
This is money they owe.

00:14:19.805 --> 00:14:22.190
They sometimes
forget it so easy.

00:14:22.190 --> 00:14:23.940
It's our money when
we give it to them.

00:14:23.940 --> 00:14:26.190
We don't give it to them
like normal creditors, that's

00:14:26.190 --> 00:14:27.780
the beginning of what's wrong.

00:14:27.780 --> 00:14:29.230
They love that funding.

00:14:29.230 --> 00:14:33.140
Insure it and we just
trust that it's OK.

00:14:33.140 --> 00:14:36.380
Trust that the regulators
protect us or something.

00:14:36.380 --> 00:14:41.440
And then they borrow in any
number of very creative ways.

00:14:41.440 --> 00:14:44.060
Overnight, against all
kinds of collaterals,

00:14:44.060 --> 00:14:47.960
they call them repos,
we can go through that.

00:14:47.960 --> 00:14:50.210
They find ways to
promise, to get somebody

00:14:50.210 --> 00:14:55.480
to give them money in exchange
for promise to pay back.

00:14:55.480 --> 00:15:01.930
And very little shareholders
money, equity, that also funds.

00:15:01.930 --> 00:15:03.000
OK?

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:08.790
They have shareholder equity in
the area of under $200 billion

00:15:08.790 --> 00:15:12.480
by shareholder's stock
price or whatever.

00:15:12.480 --> 00:15:15.030
In the market capitalization,
they're not very large.

00:15:15.030 --> 00:15:17.000
There are smaller than Apple.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:18.920
They are smaller than
many other companies.

00:15:18.920 --> 00:15:23.310
But by asset size,
they are the largest.

00:15:23.310 --> 00:15:25.790
And this is through
accounting systems

00:15:25.790 --> 00:15:30.580
that ignore trillions of dollars
of derivatives, just net them

00:15:30.580 --> 00:15:31.270
out.

00:15:31.270 --> 00:15:33.930
So they have ways to do the
accounting in such a way

00:15:33.930 --> 00:15:36.722
that we won't even see
the actual exposures.

00:15:36.722 --> 00:15:38.430
And I don't have time
to go through that,

00:15:38.430 --> 00:15:41.810
but the book explains what's
off their balance sheet that

00:15:41.810 --> 00:15:46.300
has risk in it that affects
them and everybody around them.

00:15:46.300 --> 00:15:48.700
So they'll tell you-- if
you listen to Jamie Dimon,

00:15:48.700 --> 00:15:54.130
he'll tell you it's a fortress,
fortress balance sheet.

00:15:54.130 --> 00:15:56.400
Not the image you should have.

00:15:56.400 --> 00:15:57.220
Not a fortress.

00:15:57.220 --> 00:16:01.520
Extremely fragile and
extraordinarily systemic.

00:16:01.520 --> 00:16:03.490
Too big to fail.

00:16:03.490 --> 00:16:04.890
Incredibly messy.

00:16:04.890 --> 00:16:07.120
Nobody can understand
what's going on there.

00:16:07.120 --> 00:16:09.622
You can't read their financial
statements and understand.

00:16:09.622 --> 00:16:11.830
You won't understand even
the Well's Fargo accounting

00:16:11.830 --> 00:16:12.330
statements.

00:16:12.330 --> 00:16:13.640
And people have tried.

00:16:13.640 --> 00:16:19.330
So these are very, very,
very complex as corporations.

00:16:19.330 --> 00:16:21.880
Almost impossible for
just about anybody

00:16:21.880 --> 00:16:24.970
to understand, regulate,
control, all of that.

00:16:24.970 --> 00:16:29.560
And the scandals every day give
you a hint of that as well.

00:16:29.560 --> 00:16:31.710
So how much equity
should banks have?

00:16:31.710 --> 00:16:33.180
Guess what.

00:16:33.180 --> 00:16:40.020
In the Regulation of
Basel, what's called.

00:16:40.020 --> 00:16:42.350
This is a city in
Switzerland where

00:16:42.350 --> 00:16:45.750
they sit around and decide
on minimum requirements

00:16:45.750 --> 00:16:50.080
that 27 countries are supposed
to impose on their banks.

00:16:50.080 --> 00:16:52.380
The previous regulation,
coming into the crisis,

00:16:52.380 --> 00:16:56.440
was that they should have
2%-- but not 2% of the total

00:16:56.440 --> 00:17:00.070
investment, but 2% of something
called risk-weighted assets.

00:17:00.070 --> 00:17:02.560
So this is where you
can ignore some things.

00:17:02.560 --> 00:17:05.490
Like, for example, if
a credit rating agency

00:17:05.490 --> 00:17:07.710
says that its AAA,
then you can just

00:17:07.710 --> 00:17:09.790
think of it as good as cash.

00:17:09.790 --> 00:17:12.869
Except until it's downgraded
and it's not so good as cash.

00:17:12.869 --> 00:17:15.599
Or if it's Greek
debt in the euro,

00:17:15.599 --> 00:17:18.359
if you're a German
bank or a Cyprus bank,

00:17:18.359 --> 00:17:21.640
you can lend to Greece.

00:17:21.640 --> 00:17:25.710
Don't have any assumption
that it might go down.

00:17:25.710 --> 00:17:29.630
As good as cash, even if it's
paying 20% like junk bonds.

00:17:29.630 --> 00:17:32.850
The regulation views it
as safe, because it's

00:17:32.850 --> 00:17:35.850
a promise by a government, even
though the government can't

00:17:35.850 --> 00:17:39.360
really print those
euros like Greece.

00:17:39.360 --> 00:17:40.650
And Greece defaulted.

00:17:40.650 --> 00:17:43.140
So they know we tell
you that they tripled

00:17:43.140 --> 00:17:46.230
these requirements,
tripled them from 2% to 7%.

00:17:46.230 --> 00:17:50.280
And you can go down to 4 and
1/2% of risk-weighted assets,

00:17:50.280 --> 00:17:54.450
which for the Swiss banks
is like-- the denominator

00:17:54.450 --> 00:17:58.930
of that percentage is like a
sixth of their total assets.

00:17:58.930 --> 00:18:00.870
Because there's so
many assets that

00:18:00.870 --> 00:18:04.254
get a very, very small weight.

00:18:04.254 --> 00:18:06.170
And of course, those are
the assets they love.

00:18:06.170 --> 00:18:07.890
If the regulation
thinks they're safe,

00:18:07.890 --> 00:18:10.742
but they're actually risky
and pay a lot of return,

00:18:10.742 --> 00:18:11.700
that's the place to go.

00:18:11.700 --> 00:18:16.070
And they'll all go there and
get more concentration and more

00:18:16.070 --> 00:18:19.110
interconnectedness and more
fragility in the system.

00:18:19.110 --> 00:18:21.250
So I mentioned before,
the risk weights,

00:18:21.250 --> 00:18:22.680
one source of fragility.

00:18:22.680 --> 00:18:25.370
Bad regulation.

00:18:25.370 --> 00:18:27.420
And now, because they
saw that the banks were

00:18:27.420 --> 00:18:28.681
gaming this regulation.

00:18:28.681 --> 00:18:31.180
This regulation, by the way--
Basel II-- was not implemented

00:18:31.180 --> 00:18:35.820
in the US except, guess what,
for the investment banks,

00:18:35.820 --> 00:18:38.850
the same investment banks that
got into the most trouble.

00:18:38.850 --> 00:18:42.090
It was the deposit institution
because Sheila Bair, who

00:18:42.090 --> 00:18:45.840
was the head of the FDIC,
didn't like those risk weights.

00:18:45.840 --> 00:18:49.420
They basically kept them from
manipulating these risk weights

00:18:49.420 --> 00:18:52.750
and playing with the models
of these risk weights

00:18:52.750 --> 00:18:59.010
to get the equity as low as
they could get away with.

00:18:59.010 --> 00:19:05.200
So now they put in a stop
gap measure, 3% in Basal III.

00:19:05.200 --> 00:19:12.850
The big reform, 3% of total
asset has to be equity.

00:19:12.850 --> 00:19:16.850
It used to also be that they
accepted some other things that

00:19:16.850 --> 00:19:20.570
might be equity, might absorb
losses under some conditions,

00:19:20.570 --> 00:19:24.090
and no such capital--
what they called--

00:19:24.090 --> 00:19:25.360
absorbed losses in the crisis.

00:19:25.360 --> 00:19:26.500
Everybody got paid.

00:19:26.500 --> 00:19:30.140
Even if you were promised except
in this case and that case,

00:19:30.140 --> 00:19:31.050
you were paid.

00:19:31.050 --> 00:19:33.040
So when the banks
were bailed out,

00:19:33.040 --> 00:19:34.620
all the creditors got paid.

00:19:34.620 --> 00:19:36.710
Everybody who was promised.

00:19:36.710 --> 00:19:39.760
These requirements, when I
looked at them four years ago

00:19:39.760 --> 00:19:46.070
when they came out,
were based on nonsense.

00:19:46.070 --> 00:19:47.010
Let me say the word.

00:19:47.010 --> 00:19:49.580
Bad analysis, OK,
of the trade-offs,

00:19:49.580 --> 00:19:50.960
misunderstandings, whatever.

00:19:50.960 --> 00:19:52.410
Is it tough?

00:19:52.410 --> 00:19:55.945
They'll tell you, oh, we tripled
the previous requirements.

00:19:55.945 --> 00:19:58.070
Tripling almost nothing
doesn't give you very much.

00:19:58.070 --> 00:20:00.700
So tripling this 2% to
risk-weighted assets

00:20:00.700 --> 00:20:03.950
is still ridiculously low.

00:20:03.950 --> 00:20:06.150
And in a review of
our book, John Cochran

00:20:06.150 --> 00:20:09.680
said-- because we don't come
out with precise numbers,

00:20:09.680 --> 00:20:11.520
because there's so
many issues around how

00:20:11.520 --> 00:20:14.100
you count them, and how
you-- what's the denominator,

00:20:14.100 --> 00:20:15.970
and how to deal with
risk, and all of that.

00:20:15.970 --> 00:20:16.810
How much?

00:20:16.810 --> 00:20:22.140
The point is you want that
balance sheet to absorb most

00:20:22.140 --> 00:20:24.350
of the losses under
normal conditions.

00:20:24.350 --> 00:20:27.770
You want them to remain safe
and to go get more equity when

00:20:27.770 --> 00:20:30.780
they get down into distress.

00:20:30.780 --> 00:20:33.660
That's what would
keep them functioning

00:20:33.660 --> 00:20:37.180
so they don't harm
others when they fail.

00:20:37.180 --> 00:20:42.910
Or they can have a more
orderly sort of intervention.

00:20:42.910 --> 00:20:48.730
So I can go on and on about
the benefits of forcing banks

00:20:48.730 --> 00:20:50.370
to fund with more equity.

00:20:50.370 --> 00:20:52.170
Then we can ask
ourselves, why is it

00:20:52.170 --> 00:20:54.290
that they hate it so much?

00:20:54.290 --> 00:20:54.790
OK?

00:20:54.790 --> 00:20:56.248
And there will be
reasons for that.

00:20:56.248 --> 00:20:57.760
From their perspective,
it won't be

00:20:57.760 --> 00:21:01.780
that complicated, many
reasons, strong reasons.

00:21:01.780 --> 00:21:05.460
If you have more equity,
so many things are better.

00:21:05.460 --> 00:21:06.910
They're less likely to default.

00:21:06.910 --> 00:21:09.430
They're less likely to get
distressed, less likely

00:21:09.430 --> 00:21:11.270
to have runs.

00:21:11.270 --> 00:21:13.900
The downside will be borne
by the same people who

00:21:13.900 --> 00:21:16.600
have the upside and not
by the rest of society,

00:21:16.600 --> 00:21:17.720
not the taxpayers.

00:21:17.720 --> 00:21:20.560
They won't need bailouts.

00:21:20.560 --> 00:21:23.851
When they need to sell assets
because they lost a little bit,

00:21:23.851 --> 00:21:26.350
they won't have to sell such a
big fraction of their assets.

00:21:26.350 --> 00:21:32.980
If you have equity at 2% and
you lose a tiny bit, to recover

00:21:32.980 --> 00:21:36.140
and have back to 2%, you have
to sell an enormous amount

00:21:36.140 --> 00:21:41.350
of assets because you lost
half of your equity suddenly.

00:21:41.350 --> 00:21:47.070
So your entire being, you're
not living on the edge as much.

00:21:47.070 --> 00:21:49.050
The subsidies that
are associated

00:21:49.050 --> 00:21:50.590
with being too big
to fail-- which

00:21:50.590 --> 00:21:54.200
means that those who
nobody believes will fail

00:21:54.200 --> 00:21:57.310
get creditors to give them
money under cheaper terms, which

00:21:57.310 --> 00:21:58.800
is completely established.

00:21:58.800 --> 00:22:02.790
And they still deny it,
but it's completely true.

00:22:02.790 --> 00:22:05.070
And don't write as many
conditions and all of that.

00:22:05.070 --> 00:22:08.570
So the ease with which a bank
like that can borrow-- just

00:22:08.570 --> 00:22:11.210
like Fannie and Freddie
could-- with the backing

00:22:11.210 --> 00:22:13.689
of the government
would be reduced.

00:22:13.689 --> 00:22:15.230
In other words, you
will prevent them

00:22:15.230 --> 00:22:20.000
from increasing that subsidy
to the stratosphere, which

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:22.600
is basically the worst kind
of subsidies we can give.

00:22:22.600 --> 00:22:25.020
We want to reduce them.

00:22:25.020 --> 00:22:27.330
And everything that
the banks do is

00:22:27.330 --> 00:22:30.290
distorted by being so
incredibly indebted,

00:22:30.290 --> 00:22:32.870
because heavily indebted
borrowers are just not

00:22:32.870 --> 00:22:34.310
making good decisions usually.

00:22:34.310 --> 00:22:35.660
They tend to love risk.

00:22:35.660 --> 00:22:36.839
They tend to under-invest.

00:22:36.839 --> 00:22:39.130
Homeowners that don't have
a lot of equity in the house

00:22:39.130 --> 00:22:40.500
don't invest in maintenance.

00:22:40.500 --> 00:22:44.090
That's why the foreclosures
find houses that are wrecked.

00:22:44.090 --> 00:22:46.930
They won't give a
gift to the creditor

00:22:46.930 --> 00:22:48.910
if they think they
might walk away.

00:22:48.910 --> 00:22:51.660
Similarly, companies
that are distressed

00:22:51.660 --> 00:22:53.070
are going to under-invest.

00:22:53.070 --> 00:22:55.830
Countries that are
over-indebted under-invest

00:22:55.830 --> 00:22:57.800
because there need
to be enough upside

00:22:57.800 --> 00:22:59.460
to justify the investment.

00:22:59.460 --> 00:23:01.100
Otherwise it's a
gift to the creditor.

00:23:01.100 --> 00:23:05.360
And so, the dynamics of
overhangs is very intense

00:23:05.360 --> 00:23:06.450
and risk is good.

00:23:06.450 --> 00:23:09.100
If you are under water, you're
gambling with other person's

00:23:09.100 --> 00:23:11.530
money and it's gambling
for resurrection.

00:23:11.530 --> 00:23:13.150
The downside is just as bad.

00:23:13.150 --> 00:23:16.850
And the upside,
you might be alive.

00:23:16.850 --> 00:23:18.460
So there's reason
to take the company

00:23:18.460 --> 00:23:22.122
and put it on the roulette
if there's nothing to lose.

00:23:22.122 --> 00:23:24.330
So the borrower is playing
with the creditors' money,

00:23:24.330 --> 00:23:25.220
basically.

00:23:25.220 --> 00:23:30.010
And only can win from the upside
and otherwise the creditor

00:23:30.010 --> 00:23:31.780
loses.

00:23:31.780 --> 00:23:33.820
So the history of
banking doesn't

00:23:33.820 --> 00:23:35.920
have as much
indebtedness as banks

00:23:35.920 --> 00:23:38.850
have today, which is
always in the single digit

00:23:38.850 --> 00:23:41.100
amount of equity,
however you measure it.

00:23:41.100 --> 00:23:43.790
History of banking, if you
go back to the 19th century

00:23:43.790 --> 00:23:48.070
before they had so much
support, so many safety nets,

00:23:48.070 --> 00:23:50.930
is when there were
partnerships, the partners

00:23:50.930 --> 00:23:52.190
had unlimited liability.

00:23:52.190 --> 00:23:53.540
They had to cover their losses.

00:23:53.540 --> 00:23:56.370
And they had 50% of the
investment of the bank funded

00:23:56.370 --> 00:23:58.720
by equity and 50% by deposits.

00:23:58.720 --> 00:24:02.610
So depositors needed the
bank owners to be there

00:24:02.610 --> 00:24:05.970
or they wouldn't trust the bank.

00:24:05.970 --> 00:24:08.740
Then as banks
became corporations

00:24:08.740 --> 00:24:11.060
with limited liability,
meaning the owners

00:24:11.060 --> 00:24:15.800
of the upside or the
share can walk away.

00:24:15.800 --> 00:24:20.680
They grew and as you
put in, central banks

00:24:20.680 --> 00:24:24.120
would give them support
against collateral.

00:24:24.120 --> 00:24:26.700
And you put deposit
insurance in place,

00:24:26.700 --> 00:24:30.120
so depositors didn't worry
about anything anymore.

00:24:30.120 --> 00:24:33.620
The more safety nets you
put in place, the more they

00:24:33.620 --> 00:24:38.109
loved and were able to
rely on borrowed money

00:24:38.109 --> 00:24:39.150
to fund their investment.

00:24:39.150 --> 00:24:41.740
And the more they resisted
putting their own money

00:24:41.740 --> 00:24:44.540
at risk.

00:24:44.540 --> 00:24:45.410
Why is that?

00:24:45.410 --> 00:24:50.670
It was related to
that safety net

00:24:50.670 --> 00:24:53.630
and to an effect that is
called a leverage ratchet.

00:24:53.630 --> 00:24:56.730
It's a addiction to borrowing
that is always there.

00:24:56.730 --> 00:24:59.240
A borrower always becomes a
bit addicted to borrowing,

00:24:59.240 --> 00:25:02.010
will take my
another loan as long

00:25:02.010 --> 00:25:06.640
as the creditor doesn't scream,
as long as it doesn't violate

00:25:06.640 --> 00:25:08.530
the contract that they have.

00:25:08.530 --> 00:25:12.166
By industry, I'll just
summarize this figure for you.

00:25:12.166 --> 00:25:15.610
You'll find Google and Apple and
all these high-tech companies

00:25:15.610 --> 00:25:17.980
at the place where they
just don't use any debt.

00:25:17.980 --> 00:25:20.020
This is debt-to-total.

00:25:20.020 --> 00:25:23.140
It basically depends
on the industry.

00:25:23.140 --> 00:25:25.029
And we won't go into that.

00:25:25.029 --> 00:25:26.570
I teach corporate
finance and we talk

00:25:26.570 --> 00:25:28.194
about why you might
borrow more or less

00:25:28.194 --> 00:25:30.980
but we have theories about that.

00:25:30.980 --> 00:25:36.100
And no industry and no
borrowers in the economy

00:25:36.100 --> 00:25:39.630
without any regulation
has as little equity

00:25:39.630 --> 00:25:40.690
on a regular basis.

00:25:40.690 --> 00:25:42.900
No health industry
lives like that.

00:25:42.900 --> 00:25:45.910
And there is plenty of
equity to go around.

00:25:45.910 --> 00:25:47.830
Most companies use
their retained earnings

00:25:47.830 --> 00:25:49.360
as a first source of funding.

00:25:49.360 --> 00:25:51.780
And retained earnings are
attributable to equity,

00:25:51.780 --> 00:25:52.960
it's on-board money.

00:25:52.960 --> 00:25:56.520
So if you are Warren
Buffett, you never pay out.

00:25:56.520 --> 00:25:58.060
You just keep investing.

00:25:58.060 --> 00:26:01.957
If they wanted dividends,
they can sell some shares.

00:26:01.957 --> 00:26:04.540
If you have good investments to
do, you don't need to pay out.

00:26:04.540 --> 00:26:06.620
Here are the facts.

00:26:06.620 --> 00:26:08.260
Banks will tell you
they're so special.

00:26:08.260 --> 00:26:10.971
They make long-term,
risky investments.

00:26:10.971 --> 00:26:12.720
They're not special
in that, every company

00:26:12.720 --> 00:26:16.830
makes liquid long-term
investments, very risky.

00:26:16.830 --> 00:26:18.360
Often riskier than
making a loan.

00:26:18.360 --> 00:26:20.060
Making a loan is not that risky.

00:26:20.060 --> 00:26:22.730
You diversify a little
bit over the credit risk.

00:26:22.730 --> 00:26:24.890
There is some risk
but it's not more

00:26:24.890 --> 00:26:27.700
than other industries
or companies take.

00:26:27.700 --> 00:26:30.200
It's just the way it's funded
that makes it so dangerous.

00:26:32.750 --> 00:26:35.370
On average, by market
value, companies

00:26:35.370 --> 00:26:39.760
have 70% equity,
at least ones that

00:26:39.760 --> 00:26:43.340
have access to markets for sure.

00:26:43.340 --> 00:26:47.910
And most of the
corporations and non-banks,

00:26:47.910 --> 00:26:51.292
without any regulation,
just don't borrow that much.

00:26:51.292 --> 00:26:53.250
If they did, they would
start having covenants.

00:26:53.250 --> 00:26:54.958
They'll start having
all kinds of things,

00:26:54.958 --> 00:26:57.480
even though they'll get a
tax advantage from borrowing.

00:26:57.480 --> 00:27:00.080
Everybody does, corporations.

00:27:00.080 --> 00:27:03.420
Yet, we don't see such levels
of borrowing with no regulation.

00:27:03.420 --> 00:27:05.770
But the banks love to borrow.

00:27:05.770 --> 00:27:06.520
Love to borrow.

00:27:06.520 --> 00:27:08.240
Even when they have
under 10% equity,

00:27:08.240 --> 00:27:12.120
they pay dividends,
borrow some more.

00:27:12.120 --> 00:27:12.780
That's banks.

00:27:12.780 --> 00:27:15.160
Why do they love
to borrow so much?

00:27:15.160 --> 00:27:19.620
Well, the short answer
is, works for them.

00:27:19.620 --> 00:27:21.590
Works for them on their bonuses.

00:27:21.590 --> 00:27:25.350
Works for them on the ease
with which they can borrow.

00:27:25.350 --> 00:27:29.580
Works for them to get
the upside while putting

00:27:29.580 --> 00:27:31.340
the downside on somebody else.

00:27:31.340 --> 00:27:33.300
Works for them.

00:27:33.300 --> 00:27:34.460
And they can.

00:27:34.460 --> 00:27:36.030
So why do they love to borrow?

00:27:36.030 --> 00:27:39.380
Because it works for
them and they're able to.

00:27:39.380 --> 00:27:46.660
Which is not the same for the
people, at least not as much.

00:27:46.660 --> 00:27:48.540
So there is a leveraged
ratchet effect,

00:27:48.540 --> 00:27:50.160
which affects all borrowing.

00:27:50.160 --> 00:27:54.230
Once that is in place, the
same reason or incentive

00:27:54.230 --> 00:27:57.990
for a heavy borrower to
take a little bit more risk,

00:27:57.990 --> 00:28:00.640
the downside of which is
shared by the creditor,

00:28:00.640 --> 00:28:03.260
at least if they can
walk away from the debt.

00:28:03.260 --> 00:28:06.050
Means that once you borrow,
you want to borrow more.

00:28:06.050 --> 00:28:08.320
So it becomes a bit addictive.

00:28:08.320 --> 00:28:11.240
Usually creditors will
know this and will

00:28:11.240 --> 00:28:14.090
put in all kinds of terms in
the contract to prevent that.

00:28:14.090 --> 00:28:16.160
Because they know that
the borrower is playing

00:28:16.160 --> 00:28:18.400
with their money
and will be tempted

00:28:18.400 --> 00:28:21.570
to take another loan on top
of them or equal seniority.

00:28:21.570 --> 00:28:24.040
But even if they take
a second mortgage,

00:28:24.040 --> 00:28:26.700
they're more likely to default,
which harms the first lender.

00:28:26.700 --> 00:28:29.260
So the creditors
always have to worry.

00:28:29.260 --> 00:28:33.230
But banks are able to get people
to lend to them, for example,

00:28:33.230 --> 00:28:34.310
depositors.

00:28:34.310 --> 00:28:36.430
Depositors come in, don't
worry about anything.

00:28:36.430 --> 00:28:39.040
We put money in the bank,
the bank goes and plays.

00:28:39.040 --> 00:28:42.490
Takes the upside and then--

00:28:42.490 --> 00:28:44.240
Compensation in
banking often depends

00:28:44.240 --> 00:28:46.700
on something called
return on equity.

00:28:46.700 --> 00:28:47.960
It's a whole culture thing.

00:28:47.960 --> 00:28:51.290
And they always say that this is
their job, to produce returns.

00:28:51.290 --> 00:28:53.600
Well basic corporate
finance says,

00:28:53.600 --> 00:28:55.920
just taking risk
by itself, anybody

00:28:55.920 --> 00:28:59.980
can do, why would I pay you
the big bucks just to do that?

00:28:59.980 --> 00:29:02.450
Anybody can take risk and
get appropriate return

00:29:02.450 --> 00:29:03.390
in these markets.

00:29:03.390 --> 00:29:07.080
So the notion that your job
is to produce returns, well,

00:29:07.080 --> 00:29:09.076
do you produce more
returns than is

00:29:09.076 --> 00:29:10.450
reasonable for
the risk you take?

00:29:10.450 --> 00:29:11.740
That's the question.

00:29:11.740 --> 00:29:15.230
So producing returns is
not even an objective,

00:29:15.230 --> 00:29:18.800
let alone makes any
sense as an objective,

00:29:18.800 --> 00:29:20.280
if you don't adjust for risk.

00:29:20.280 --> 00:29:23.040
The more leverage, the
more risk for the equity,

00:29:23.040 --> 00:29:24.460
because it's leveraged.

00:29:24.460 --> 00:29:30.320
So all this kind of focus on
taking risk-- basically, being

00:29:30.320 --> 00:29:34.680
paid to gamble-- gives
bankers an incentive to say,

00:29:34.680 --> 00:29:36.790
I got to borrow this much.

00:29:36.790 --> 00:29:39.970
If you don't let me,
terrible things will happen.

00:29:39.970 --> 00:29:41.270
That kind of thing.

00:29:41.270 --> 00:29:47.290
So the scale is tipped for the
bankers in favor of borrowing.

00:29:47.290 --> 00:29:50.570
Put the deposits in place that
we all need for payment system.

00:29:50.570 --> 00:29:52.870
But now, the extra
dollar that they fund.

00:29:52.870 --> 00:29:54.450
Where will they want to take it?

00:29:54.450 --> 00:29:55.250
From that.

00:29:55.250 --> 00:29:59.260
Never from retained earnings
or equity or not very much.

00:29:59.260 --> 00:30:03.880
But all these reasons why
they like to basically mean

00:30:03.880 --> 00:30:06.430
that it's cheaper
for them on account

00:30:06.430 --> 00:30:11.710
of somebody else
bearing the costs.

00:30:11.710 --> 00:30:15.280
They save but somebody
else is paying.

00:30:15.280 --> 00:30:18.070
There's nothing about it
that comes out of nowhere,

00:30:18.070 --> 00:30:19.490
there's no magic to it.

00:30:19.490 --> 00:30:26.230
For society, what
would be much better

00:30:26.230 --> 00:30:30.150
is if they fund with
much more equity.

00:30:30.150 --> 00:30:31.880
So here's another
visual for you.

00:30:31.880 --> 00:30:33.640
The bank can fund
loans-- suppose

00:30:33.640 --> 00:30:35.770
we wanted the loans
that they fund.

00:30:35.770 --> 00:30:38.860
You could imagine a company
producing just about anything.

00:30:38.860 --> 00:30:40.700
And they need to get the money.

00:30:40.700 --> 00:30:45.700
Well, they can get the money
from debt or from equity.

00:30:45.700 --> 00:30:48.510
Now, the more debt
that they use,

00:30:48.510 --> 00:30:53.320
the more they pollute
the rest of the economy.

00:30:53.320 --> 00:30:55.790
So think of excessive
indebtedness

00:30:55.790 --> 00:30:58.270
as a pollutant for the system.

00:30:58.270 --> 00:31:01.050
Because it introduces all
these fragilities, few can pay,

00:31:01.050 --> 00:31:03.680
then it cascades
through, and all of that.

00:31:03.680 --> 00:31:04.510
Now what do we do?

00:31:04.510 --> 00:31:07.260
We have policies in place
that subsidize and encourage

00:31:07.260 --> 00:31:10.650
and enable more and
make the debt more

00:31:10.650 --> 00:31:12.940
attractive to the banks.

00:31:12.940 --> 00:31:16.730
They respond by
using a lot of debt

00:31:16.730 --> 00:31:18.790
and just a little bit of equity.

00:31:18.790 --> 00:31:21.840
And therefore pollute more.

00:31:21.840 --> 00:31:23.920
So in other words,
we have a situation

00:31:23.920 --> 00:31:28.701
in which we can get, maybe, some
cheap product if we subsidize

00:31:28.701 --> 00:31:29.200
it.

00:31:29.200 --> 00:31:32.800
Anything that you can subsidize,
you can get the price, maybe,

00:31:32.800 --> 00:31:34.940
the subsidies to pass on, maybe.

00:31:34.940 --> 00:31:38.240
But then, we've got
to clean up the river.

00:31:38.240 --> 00:31:40.080
So how did we get?

00:31:40.080 --> 00:31:41.050
The bankers are happy.

00:31:41.050 --> 00:31:42.530
Do they pass these subsidies?

00:31:42.530 --> 00:31:43.990
There's actually
a little evidence

00:31:43.990 --> 00:31:46.490
that the more they
lever, the more

00:31:46.490 --> 00:31:48.070
the rest of the economy wins.

00:31:48.070 --> 00:31:49.850
Basically what
happens to lending,

00:31:49.850 --> 00:31:53.220
in short, is you get
too much and too little

00:31:53.220 --> 00:31:54.830
of it sometimes
at the same time.

00:31:54.830 --> 00:31:58.060
Get them to love risky
loans, credit card loans,

00:31:58.060 --> 00:32:00.740
they send everybody a
credit card, 20% interest.

00:32:00.740 --> 00:32:02.329
And at the same
time, they don't want

00:32:02.329 --> 00:32:03.870
to make the boring
business loan that

00:32:03.870 --> 00:32:05.420
doesn't have enough upside.

00:32:05.420 --> 00:32:08.529
So people would complain they
don't get loans, but then

00:32:08.529 --> 00:32:10.070
some other people
get too many loans.

00:32:10.070 --> 00:32:13.360
And they'll price the loans.

00:32:13.360 --> 00:32:15.870
Making loans is an
investment anybody can make.

00:32:15.870 --> 00:32:20.050
We don't know if they
actually pass it on.

00:32:20.050 --> 00:32:23.610
What we do know is if you
look at it carefully--

00:32:23.610 --> 00:32:26.140
and of course they have their
own industry-sponsored studies

00:32:26.140 --> 00:32:28.720
that deny this--
there is no evidence

00:32:28.720 --> 00:32:32.640
that economies are scaling
banking beyond $100 billion.

00:32:32.640 --> 00:32:35.316
If you correct for the fact
that the bigger you grow,

00:32:35.316 --> 00:32:37.940
the more subsidies you actually
have, so therefore your profits

00:32:37.940 --> 00:32:39.780
are based on subsidized funding.

00:32:39.780 --> 00:32:42.870
Once you correct for
that, there is no evidence

00:32:42.870 --> 00:32:46.210
that the largest the bank, the
more efficient the bank is,

00:32:46.210 --> 00:32:50.020
in terms of getting
product out of the bank,

00:32:50.020 --> 00:32:51.560
getting work out of the bank.

00:32:51.560 --> 00:32:54.290
There is evidence that the
subsidies-- which are enormous.

00:32:54.290 --> 00:32:56.480
This shows you,
essentially, what

00:32:56.480 --> 00:32:59.210
the banks would have had to
pay if they wanted somebody

00:32:59.210 --> 00:33:03.770
to insure their debt when they
were so close to the abyss.

00:33:03.770 --> 00:33:09.210
Of course, for insurance,
it's worth less in good times.

00:33:09.210 --> 00:33:14.960
And of course, when you need
it, if you had to buy it,

00:33:14.960 --> 00:33:15.870
you'd have pay a lot.

00:33:15.870 --> 00:33:18.310
So the value of the guarantees
that the banks were getting

00:33:18.310 --> 00:33:20.120
was enormous around the crisis.

00:33:20.120 --> 00:33:23.440
They would have really gone
broke if they didn't have

00:33:23.440 --> 00:33:25.560
them, many of them.

00:33:25.560 --> 00:33:27.000
So what do we have?

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:29.680
We have a system where we
perversely subsidize pollution

00:33:29.680 --> 00:33:32.770
even though there's sort of
a clean alternative funding.

00:33:32.770 --> 00:33:35.020
Once deposits are in place,
you can always add equity.

00:33:35.020 --> 00:33:38.460
You can buy anything with it but
it backs up your liabilities,

00:33:38.460 --> 00:33:40.160
self-insurance.

00:33:40.160 --> 00:33:44.410
And so the more indebtedness,
the better their lives are.

00:33:44.410 --> 00:33:47.470
They produce more
average returns, maybe.

00:33:47.470 --> 00:33:49.230
They get better compensation.

00:33:49.230 --> 00:33:53.650
And we're drinking the
polluted water, basically.

00:33:53.650 --> 00:33:55.221
So there's a large
cost to society

00:33:55.221 --> 00:33:56.470
for these implicit guarantees.

00:33:56.470 --> 00:33:57.928
The thing about
implicit guarantees

00:33:57.928 --> 00:33:59.980
is you don't see
them all the time.

00:33:59.980 --> 00:34:04.060
You think it's free to just say,
oh, I'll guarantee your debt.

00:34:04.060 --> 00:34:06.952
In the book, we have a chapter
in which our homeowner/borrower

00:34:06.952 --> 00:34:11.710
, Kate, has an aunt Claire.

00:34:11.710 --> 00:34:13.652
And Aunt Claire
says, buy a house.

00:34:13.652 --> 00:34:14.860
I'll guarantee your mortgage.

00:34:14.860 --> 00:34:16.370
She gets a great
loan from the bank.

00:34:16.370 --> 00:34:18.600
The bank doesn't care if
she puts a down payment

00:34:18.600 --> 00:34:20.300
because Aunt Claire is rich.

00:34:20.300 --> 00:34:23.710
But when Aunt Claire
tells Kate that she

00:34:23.710 --> 00:34:27.770
can go build a corporation
and invest in anything

00:34:27.770 --> 00:34:32.340
and she'll guarantee her
debt-- blank guarantees,

00:34:32.340 --> 00:34:35.580
blanket guarantees-- she
can go to Las Vegas, too.

00:34:35.580 --> 00:34:36.710
She takes the upside.

00:34:36.710 --> 00:34:38.270
If it doesn't work out.

00:34:38.270 --> 00:34:40.850
I mean, she pays dividends
to herself on the upside.

00:34:40.850 --> 00:34:42.650
On the downside, she
just borrows more.

00:34:42.650 --> 00:34:45.250
Until she ruins her
aunt, of course.

00:34:45.250 --> 00:34:48.150
And we've seen countries
being harmed by this.

00:34:48.150 --> 00:34:50.909
Iceland being one of
them, Ireland another one,

00:34:50.909 --> 00:34:52.350
Cyprus another one.

00:34:52.350 --> 00:34:53.469
That's how bad it can get.

00:34:53.469 --> 00:34:57.060
For the others, it's
still incredibly costly.

00:34:57.060 --> 00:34:58.110
So the big picture.

00:34:58.110 --> 00:35:00.150
We want to shuffle the claims.

00:35:00.150 --> 00:35:04.800
All investments can be done
if banks figuratively have

00:35:04.800 --> 00:35:05.800
more equity.

00:35:05.800 --> 00:35:07.840
I don't even care
that they grow,

00:35:07.840 --> 00:35:09.300
as long as it's with equity.

00:35:09.300 --> 00:35:10.570
They won't grow.

00:35:10.570 --> 00:35:13.560
They will begin to respond
more to market signals.

00:35:13.560 --> 00:35:17.530
Conglomerates in the
'80s, broke from being

00:35:17.530 --> 00:35:19.670
bloated and inefficient.

00:35:19.670 --> 00:35:22.560
And started being more
streamlined and more nimble.

00:35:22.560 --> 00:35:26.860
These banks are monstrous,
inefficiently monstrous.

00:35:26.860 --> 00:35:29.490
If they had to fund
in market prices

00:35:29.490 --> 00:35:32.870
and not in subsidized way and
would have less incentives

00:35:32.870 --> 00:35:36.760
to be so big and complicated,
in order to be too big to fail,

00:35:36.760 --> 00:35:41.640
then we might begin to see more
efficient institutions being

00:35:41.640 --> 00:35:43.190
formed for market forces.

00:35:43.190 --> 00:35:46.660
Right now, the markets are
failing to correct all of that.

00:35:46.660 --> 00:35:49.640
The incentives are all bad.

00:35:49.640 --> 00:35:50.710
How do you make it work?

00:35:50.710 --> 00:35:53.900
Well, it's a
challenge but you've

00:35:53.900 --> 00:35:56.010
got to focus on
what you need to do.

00:35:56.010 --> 00:35:58.400
First of all, they have
to increase their equity.

00:35:58.400 --> 00:35:59.470
And they have earnings.

00:35:59.470 --> 00:36:02.730
Just the other week,
the Fed, again,

00:36:02.730 --> 00:36:06.170
allowed them to pay out because
the standards are so low.

00:36:06.170 --> 00:36:10.810
Even in the US, when
it's 5% instead of 3%,

00:36:10.810 --> 00:36:11.790
it's still ridiculous.

00:36:11.790 --> 00:36:13.540
And it's by counting
numbers and all kinds

00:36:13.540 --> 00:36:16.850
of weights and models
that you shouldn't trust

00:36:16.850 --> 00:36:17.850
and all kinds of things.

00:36:17.850 --> 00:36:19.550
I'll talk about stress
test in a second.

00:36:19.550 --> 00:36:23.320
They tell you that
everything's OK.

00:36:23.320 --> 00:36:25.740
If they are viable banks,
they can raise equity.

00:36:25.740 --> 00:36:27.420
Anybody can at
appropriate prices.

00:36:27.420 --> 00:36:28.691
They just don't want to.

00:36:28.691 --> 00:36:29.690
They just don't want to.

00:36:29.690 --> 00:36:31.190
They have to be
told, you know what?

00:36:31.190 --> 00:36:32.239
Too bad.

00:36:32.239 --> 00:36:34.030
The only reason you
can even live like that

00:36:34.030 --> 00:36:36.680
is because people
believe you can't fail.

00:36:36.680 --> 00:36:38.810
That's why people
give you money.

00:36:38.810 --> 00:36:41.830
Go to equity investors and
see what they'll give you.

00:36:41.830 --> 00:36:42.570
If you can't.

00:36:42.570 --> 00:36:47.190
If you tell me you can't at
all have anybody give you

00:36:47.190 --> 00:36:49.630
$1 or a euro for
your shares, I've

00:36:49.630 --> 00:36:53.360
got to worry you might
be a zombie bank.

00:36:53.360 --> 00:36:54.670
And Citi could be one of those.

00:36:54.670 --> 00:36:59.730
Citi was brought back
to life multiple times

00:36:59.730 --> 00:37:02.200
over the last
however many years.

00:37:02.200 --> 00:37:08.701
There is it an institution
that's truly problematic.

00:37:08.701 --> 00:37:11.560
Some claim it and
Bank of America--

00:37:11.560 --> 00:37:14.030
the ones that made the
stupidest acquisitions

00:37:14.030 --> 00:37:17.960
and lost a lot of
money, became insolvent,

00:37:17.960 --> 00:37:22.790
and are only alive today
because of all the supports.

00:37:22.790 --> 00:37:25.620
So Basel has lots of flaws.

00:37:25.620 --> 00:37:29.140
This regulation is
not a good regulation.

00:37:29.140 --> 00:37:31.860
They learned a few
lessons but not enough.

00:37:31.860 --> 00:37:36.960
And there is a lot of bad
policies around banking.

00:37:36.960 --> 00:37:39.680
They always kick the can down
the road, especially in Europe

00:37:39.680 --> 00:37:40.360
right now.

00:37:40.360 --> 00:37:43.119
They'll say, oh, we
can't get any bank fail.

00:37:43.119 --> 00:37:44.160
We're just going to wait.

00:37:44.160 --> 00:37:46.760
We're going to support them this
way and support them that way

00:37:46.760 --> 00:37:47.890
and hope they make a loan.

00:37:47.890 --> 00:37:49.640
But it's the weakness
of the banks that's

